("description_anti_fooling_paint", "Description:^^This anti fooling paint protects boats and ships from fooling and from barnacles which grow on the ship hull. It is made by Farbius, only he knows the recept.^^Background:^^Barnacles are small crustaceans that attach themselves to submerged surfaces, including the hulls of ships. This process is known as biofouling."),
("description_didos_underwear", "Description:^^Whisper-thin silk said to have belonged to the fabled Queen of Carthage, radiating an air of timeless allure.^^Background:^^Some retards buy the underwear of women to sniff on it. As part of an Emperor-event player may discovers the retarded character of such people."),

("description_aegis", "Description:^^This is the shield of Zeus, forged by Hephaestus. It features the head of a Gorgon.^^Background:^^In Greek mythology, the aegis (or aigis) is closely associated with Zeus, the king of the gods. The aegis is typically described as a protective cloak or shield associated with divine power. It is sometimes depicted as bearing the head of Gorgon, a creature with snakes for hair whose gaze could turn people to stone. The aegis was a symbol of divine protection and intimidation, often used by Zeus or his daughter Athena. In some myths, other gods and goddesses are also described as using the aegis."),
("description_caesars_sword", "Description:^^This is the gladius of Gaius Julius Caesar. It is called 'Crocea Mors', which is Latin for 'yellow death'. Everyone who is struck with the sword either has his head chopped off or else was so wounded that they have no hope of ever recovering.^^Background:^^According to legends, when Caesar was invading Britannia, he fought against a Britanic Lord called Nennius. Caesar struck Nennius a blow to the head, but his sword got stuck in Nennius's shield. After they separated in the melée, Nennius threw away his own sword and attacked the Romans with Caesar's sword, killing many, including the tribune Quintus Laberius Durus. Fifteen days after the battle Nennius died of his head wound, and was buried at London (the 'City of the Trinovantes'), near the North Gate. Caesar's sword, Crocea Mors, was buried with him."),
("description_caesars_sword_melee", "Description:^^This is the gladius of Gaius Julius Caesar. It is called 'Crocea Mors', which is Latin for 'yellow death'. Everyone who is struck with the sword either has his head chopped off or else was so wounded that they have no hope of ever recovering.^^Background:^^According to legends, when Caesar was invading Britannia, he fought against a Britanic Lord called Nennius. Caesar struck Nennius a blow to the head, but his sword got stuck in Nennius's shield. After they separated in the melée, Nennius threw away his own sword and attacked the Romans with Caesar's sword, killing many, including the tribune Quintus Laberius Durus. Fifteen days after the battle Nennius died of his head wound, and was buried at London (the 'City of the Trinovantes'), near the North Gate. Caesar's sword, Crocea Mors, was buried with him."),
("description_maske", "Description:^^This is a mask with a cloak. It is worn by Bacchus to hide his face.^^Background:^^Nothing more to say."),
("description_roman_rich_vitellius", "Description:^^This body item is Vitellius fat gut. You can't obtain it.^^Background:^^Aulus Vitellius was known for his corpulent and indulgent lifestyle. Historical accounts describe Vitellius as being overweight and excessively fond of luxury, gluttony, and extravagant banquets. His physical appearance, particularly his obesity, is often highlighted in historical sources."),
